00:18:42.820 --> 00:18:44.695
And, all of a sudden,
you get these giant 30,

00:18:44.695 --> 00:18:46.390
40 foot high waves.

00:18:46.390 --> 00:18:50.300
And you could rightfully think
the whole ocean is in upheaval.

00:18:50.300 --> 00:18:51.370
Jeez.

00:18:51.370 --> 00:18:53.530
But if you can do a
cross-section of the ocean

00:18:53.530 --> 00:18:55.495
out there, you'd
realize that there's

00:18:55.495 --> 00:18:59.350
these little 30-foot waves,
but the ocean, in reality,

00:18:59.350 --> 00:19:01.150
is over a mile deep.

00:19:01.150 --> 00:19:02.680
And while the
nature of the ocean

00:19:02.680 --> 00:19:06.400
can be very turbulent and
tsunami-esque on the surface,

00:19:06.400 --> 00:19:09.850
in reality, the ocean
at its depth is silent.

00:19:09.850 --> 00:19:11.255
And so we say--

00:19:11.255 --> 00:19:12.090
Is this OK?

00:19:12.090 --> 00:19:13.881
RUSSELL BRAND: Yeah,
